06167nam a22008055i 9780824888930DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021012053  a9780824888930  a(DE-B1597)573123  a(OCoLC)1252421581  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI00aPL777.33.H59bS36 2021 4aPL777.33.H59bS36 2021eb 7aLIT0080302bisacsh04a895.63/20935380866422231 aSchmidt-Hori, Sachi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTales of Idolized Boys :bMale-Male Love in Medieval Japanese Buddhist Narratives /cSachi Schmidt-Hori. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b19 color, 5 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrelude -- tIntroduction Becoming a Chigo -- tChapter 1 Chigo Monogatari Central Themes, Archetypes, and the Politics and Aesthetics of Acolyte-Monk Love -- tChapter 2 A Booklet of Acolytes An Erotic Handscroll of Five Capricious Boys -- tChapter 3 The Mountain An Acolyte Tale of Traversals, Transformations, and Triumph -- tChapter 4 The Chigo Known as Miss Rookie: When an Acolyte Falls in Love with an Aristocratic Lady -- tEpilogue -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn medieval Japan (14th–16th centuries), it was customary for elite families to entrust their young sons to the care of renowned Buddhist priests from whom they received a premier education in Buddhist scriptures, poetry, music, and dance. When the boys reached adolescence, some underwent coming-of-age rites, others entered the priesthood, and several extended their education, becoming chigo, or Buddhist acolytes. Chigo served their masters as personal attendants and as sexual partners. During religious ceremonies—adorned in colorful robes, their faces made up and hair styled in long ponytails—they entertained local donors and pilgrims with music and dance. Stories of acolytes (chigo monogatari) from the fourteenth to sixteenth centuries form the basis of the present volume, an original and detailed literary analysis of six tales coupled with a thorough examination of the socio-political, religious, and cultural matrices that produced these texts.Author Sachi Schmidt-Hori begins by delineating various dimensions of chigo (the chigo “title,” personal names, gender, sexuality, class, politics, and religiosity) to show the complexity of this cultural construct—the chigo as a triply liminal figure who is neither male nor female, child nor adult, human nor deity. A modern reception history of chigo monogatari follows, revealing, not surprisingly, that the tales have often been interpreted through cultural paradigms rooted in historical moments and worldviews far removed from the original. From the 1950s to 1980s, research on chigo was hindered by widespread homophobic prejudice. More recently, aversion to the age gap in historical master-acolyte relations has prevented scholars from analyzing the religious and political messages underlying the genre. Schmidt-Hori’s work calls for a shift in the hermeneutic strategies applied to chigo and chigo monogatari and puts forth both a nuanced historicization of social constructs such as gender, sexuality, age, and agency, and a mode of reading propelled by curiosity and introspection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBuddhist acolytes in literature. 0aBuddhist acolyteszJapanxHistory. 0aBuddhist stories, JapanesexHistory and criticism. 0aJapanese fictiony1185-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aMale homosexuality in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Japanese.2bisacs